comment_regular_data.body:
I was avoiding iterating over all windows, because i thought that might be slow. But ig I ended up implementing something complex that can be done easily :)

This works fine, so ig we go with this version instead
```diff
-  refresh_size(term, buf);
+  bool size_refreshed = refresh_size(term, buf);
   refresh_scrollback(term, buf);
   refresh_screen(term, buf);
+  if (size_refreshed) {
+    FOR_ALL_TAB_WINDOWS(tp, wp) {
+      if (wp->w_buffer == buf && wp->w_leftcol) {
+        wp->w_leftcol = 0;
+        curs_columns(wp, true);
+      }
+    }
+  }
```

Yeah I think that's better. It's simple and resizing shouldn't occur often enough for performance to be a concern. (plus `curs_columns` isn't always called for non-current windows, so a loop may have been needed anyway; `adjust_topline_cursor` is doing a lot of looping anyways)

Be sure to add some tests, and maybe a comment above the loop like:
```c
// Resized window may have scrolled horizontally to keep its cursor in-view using the terminal's old
// size. Reset the scroll, and let curs_columns correct it if that sends the cursor out-of-view.
```
